\begin_layout Section
The AS-AD Model 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an AS–AD model for a closed economy.
 Output in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the long-run level of output is 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Inflation in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}$
\end_inset

 and the inflation target is 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central bank sets the nominal interest rate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

,
 according to a Taylor-rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i_{t}=\overline{r}+\pi_{t}^{e}+\alpha_{1}(\pi_{t}-\pi^{*})+\alpha_{2}(y_{t}-\bar{y}),\label{eq:taylor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{r}$
\end_inset

 is the long-run real interest rate,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{t}^{e}$
\end_inset

 are inflation expectations,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 measures the response to the inflation gap,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{2}>0$
\end_inset

 measures the response to the output gap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Market clearing in the goods market requires
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t}-\bar{y}=-b(i_{t}-\pi_{t}^{e}-\overline{r})+v_{t},\label{eq:market_clearing}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $b>0$
\end_inset

 is the real-rate sensitivity,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\emph on
demand shock
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together these two equation imply
\series bold
 
\series default
the 
\series bold
Aggregate Demand (AD) curve
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{t}=\pi^{*}-\frac{1}{\alpha}\Big[(y_{t}-\bar{y})-z_{t}\Big],\label{eq:AD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha & \equiv\frac{b\alpha_{1}}{1+b\alpha_{2}}>0\\
z_{t} & \equiv\frac{v_{t}}{1+b\alpha_{2}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Short-Run Aggregate Supply (SRAS) curve 
\series default
is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{t}=\pi_{t}^{e}+\gamma(y_{t}-\bar{y}),\label{eq:SRAS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma>0$
\end_inset

 is the slope.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inflation expectation are adaptive and given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{t}^{e}=\phi\pi_{t-1}^{e}+(1-\phi)\pi_{t-1},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

 is the weight on the expectation in the previous period,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\phi$
\end_inset

 is weight on inflation in the previous period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In each period,
 the model is in equilibrium with 
\begin_inset Formula $AD=AS$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
y_{t}^{\star} & =\bar{y}+\frac{1}{\frac{1}{\alpha}+\gamma}\left[\pi^{*}-\pi_{t}^{e}+\frac{1}{\alpha}z_{t}\right]\label{eq:y_eq}\\
\pi_{t}^{\star} & =\pi_{t}^{e}+\frac{\gamma}{\frac{1}{\alpha}+\gamma}\left[\pi^{*}-\pi_{t}^{e}+\frac{1}{\alpha}z_{t}\right].\label{eq:pi_eq}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

